He oversimplified the differences, ddr5 isn't better but rather a different architecture that is the future because implementations of most compiled languages target it.
Game engines are a good example of why ddr5 rams are important because they are highly optimized at every level of compiler (of c++ or c#) and the optimization normally is to use cache as much as they can, which avoids: pipe stalling, cache issues caused by polymorphism, and any other performance bottlenecks caused by cache misses. This is primarily because they use data oriented designs, and rely on the sheer genius of implementation defined optimizations in the standard library and the language itself (that target caches). The love of cache by game engines means that they need ddr5 more since it has higher throughput than latency. Basically ddr5 isn't faster than ddr4 but it has a higher rate throughput.

A better example of where ddr5 is useless/less important is for operating system performance, browser performance, network speed, etc because most of these applications heavily depend on pointers. In the case of browsers: you have the V8 engine that is interpreted hence (in concept) not very cache friendly, in the case of operating systems you have structures in memory that the CPU depends on for process multiplexing, interrupt handling, paging,etc, and in the case of network communications: you need constant latency if let's suppose, you are using https to watch a 4k (a good idea since your cookies are still visible without https), you would need pointers, and in particular, you would need pointers to manage various pieces of http (communication related) information, which again would cause cache mises when combined with the fact that you would have to load that information(by decrypting),process it, and then point to the important http communication related info using pointers(the evil that causes cache misses), all of this would be discarded as soon as you don't need that information which happens quite often since google tends to (constantly) change some of their cookies(and other information that I can't understand) in their network communication on a per packet bases. What I said always applies to operating systems in concept, but at times don't apply to browsers and networking, but you get the point on what I am talking about.

The reason behind why you see improvement in the performance of certain AMD CPUs as opposed to Intel is because of differing architecture, that is: Intel's CPUs may not rely on pipelining and cache performance as much as AMD CPUs do, but sadly we can't  be sure about that since both of them make everything about their CPUs private,except for the frontend of the CPU needed for systems/compiler_backend programming, which does contain some information that could help you do some guesses, but even that is nearly impossible to read and far more impossible to make sense of, it's as if a bunch of nerds come up with a book to offend people who love computers. We do get some cache size details, but we can't know how it's utilized by the processer.

All this is to say that never trust every piece of information that someone claims to be true, for example, When I was 14, I was  taught that fragmented information is faster to process hence they break up ipv4 packets while sending packets to some target, which is total nonsense, if you read the RFC's and some routing protocols manuals for ipv4, you would find out that ipv4 packets are only broken up when the link(of a router) next in line (of the most efficient route) has a smaller MTU(it can't process something as big as what you are sending). This is just one mistake coupled with calling the fragmentation as "framing" was an insult to injury caused by many other mistake
